docs {
  # OAuth2 — Sign in with Twitch

  Entry point of the Twitch OAuth2 login flow. Hitting this URL in a browser
  redirects the user to Twitch's consent screen. After consent, Twitch calls
  back to `/api/login/oauth2/code/twitch` (handled by Spring Security), which
  triggers `OAuth2AuthenticationSuccessHandler` and redirects the browser to
  `${app.frontend-url}/`.

  > Bruno cannot replay the full flow because it requires interactive consent
  > on Twitch's domain. This entry exists to document the endpoint; copy the
  > URL into a browser to actually exercise it.

  ## Behaviour

  - **Browser**: 302 redirect to Twitch's OAuth consent screen.
  - **Server (after callback)**: fetches the Twitch user via Helix
    (`https://api.twitch.tv/helix/users` — note the required `Client-Id` header
    and `data` array unwrap, both handled by `CheckpointOAuth2UserService`),
    creates or links a local user, sets a `JSESSIONID` cookie, then
    302-redirects to the frontend.

  ## Account resolution rules

  1. If a user already exists with `(provider=TWITCH, providerId=<id>)`, returns it.
  2. Else if a user exists with the same email, links the Twitch identity to that account.
  3. Else creates a new user with `password=null`, `provider=TWITCH`, a unique pseudo derived from the Twitch display_name (or login), and the `USER` role.

  Banned users are rejected with redirect to `/login?error=oauth_banned`.
  Any other failure redirects to `/login?error=oauth_failed`.

  ## Scopes

  - `user:read:email` — required to retrieve the user's email from Helix.

  ## Configuration

  Requires `TWITCH_CLIENT_ID` and `TWITCH_CLIENT_SECRET` to be set in the environment
  (Doppler in dev/prod). Without them the OAuth2 chain is dormant and this URL returns 404.
}
